04763nam a22007215i 9781442686274DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222008onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426862747 a10.3138/97814426862742doi  a(DE-B1597)626588  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aF1039.5.H17bN45 2008 7aSOC0310002bisacsh04a971.6/225041 aNelson, Jennifer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRazing Africville /cJennifer Nelson. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Authoring Africville: A Selected History -- t2 Placing Africville: The Making of the Slum -- t3 Knowing Africville: Telling Stories of Blackness -- t4 Razing Africville: Fusing Spatial Management and Racist Discourse -- t5 Reconciling Africville: The Politics of Dreaming and Forgetting -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the 1960s, the city of Halifax razed the black community of Africville under a program of urban renewal and ‘slum clearance.’ The city defended its actions by citing the deplorable living conditions in Africville, ignoring its own role in the creation of these conditions through years of neglect and the refusal of essential services. In the 1980s, the city created a park on Africville’s former site, which has been a place of protest and commemoration for black citizens since its opening. As yet, however, the city has not issued a formal apology to Africville residents and has paid no further compensation.Razing Africville examines this history as the prolonged eviction of a community from its own space. By examining a variety of sources – urban planning texts, city council documents, news media, and academic accounts – Jennifer J. Nelson illustrates how Africville went from a slum to a problem to be solved and, more recently, to a public space in which past violence is rendered invisible. Reading historical texts as a critical map of decision-making, she argues that the ongoing measures taken to regulate black bodies and spaces amount to a ‘geography of racism.’ Through a geographic lens, therefore, she manages to analyse ways in which race requires space and how the control of space is a necessary component of delineating and controlling people.A much needed re-examination of an important historical example, Razing Africville applies contemporary spatial theory to the situation in Africville and offers critical observations about the function of racism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBlacksxRace identityzNova ScotiazHalifax. 0aBlacksxRelocationzNova ScotiazHalifaxxHistoryy20th century. 0aBlacksxRelocationzNova ScotiazHalifaxxHistory. 0aEvictionzNova ScotiazHalifaxxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacismxGovernment policyzNova ScotiazHalifaxxHistory. 0aRacismzNova ScotiazHalifaxxHistoryy20th century. 0aUrban renewalzNova ScotiazHalifaxxHistoryy20th century. 0aWhitesxRace identityzNova ScotiazHalifax. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268627440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442686274423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442686274/original  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA1